on":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Byrches was born in 1343, in Blaby, Leicestershire, England, her father, Sir William de Leicestershire Byrches, was 28 and her mother, Lady William de Leicestershire Byrches, was 24. She married William de Horton about 1370, in Mowsley, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1374, in Mowsley, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1343–1374":"1343–1374","1330–1413":"1330–1413","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1372–1413":"1372–1413","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1315":"1315","1413":"1413","1343":"1343","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","1372":"1372","about 1372":"umbes 1372","Mowsley, Leicestershire, England":"Mowsley, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blaby, Leicestershire, England":"Blaby, Leicestershire, England","Woodcote, Shropshire, England":"Woodcote, Shropshire, England","MOWSLEY, Leciestershire, England":"Mowsley, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mowsley, Market Harborough, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":